First set `action`:
- `"update"` when the user refers to an EXISTING ticket above and wants to change it (e.g. "assign
  this ticket to me", "set its due date", "make that one high priority", "rename it"). Put what they
  pointed to in `target_ref` (a name fragment, or "this"/"it"/"last" if they just said "this ticket"),
  and leave `tickets` empty. Do NOT create a new ticket for a change request.
- `"create"` otherwise.

Return a `ClickUpPlan`:
- `tickets`: the ticket(s) to create. If the user wants the project's existing tasks pushed to
  ClickUp ("create tickets for all the tasks", "push these to ClickUp"), return ONE ticket per task
  (task title → `name`, task description → `description`, set `source_task_id` to the task id). If
  the user describes a SPECIFIC ad-hoc ticket ("create a ticket to call the client Friday"), return
  just that one ticket with a clear, concise `name`.
- **Never invent a ticket title.** If the user asks to create a ticket but gives NO concrete subject
  to title it from (e.g. "create a ticket", "make a ClickUp ticket but no details needed"), return
  an EMPTY `tickets` list and set `needs_title: true`. Do NOT make up a placeholder like "Ad-hoc
  task".
- `needs_title`: true ONLY when the user wants a ticket but provided no subject to name it from.
- `skip_questions`: true when the user has ALREADY settled the details — i.e. they explicitly say
  they don't want a due date / priority / assignee ("no due date, priority or assignee", "just
  create it", "no details needed"), OR they already stated the details they want in the message.
  false when the user said nothing about due date / priority / assignee (so we should ask).
- For each ticket, fill what the user explicitly gave: `priority` (ClickUp scale 1=Urgent, 2=High,
  3=Normal, 4=Low; default 3 if unspecified), `due_date` (natural language as written, else null).
  Leave `assignees` null here (assignee resolution happens later with the member list).
- Never fabricate work, dates, or assignees the user didn't mention.
